[Student "S"]
{When the bidding gets high in a hurry you sometimes have to guess what you can make. East plays 4\S. South leads the \HK.

And it looks like you are too high. Assuming the trumps split 2-1, you still have one \H loser, two \D losers and one \C loser.

You win the \HA and play a \S to your \SK. North discards a \D! 

From bad to worse. Now you must add a \S loser to the four you already had. Are you finished?

No, never give up. South has a bunch of \Hs and 3 \Ss, so he cannot have many \Ds and \Cs. If you can eliminate those and then throw him in it should work to your advantage.

Play your \SA, the \DA and the \C A K. South follows to everything.

You've done all you can do. Now play the \H10 to South's high \H. 

South has just won his side's first trick with the \HJ. He now plays the \SQ, winning his side's second trick.

Now, South is still on lead, and he has nothing in his hand but good \Hs. So he leads one of them, and you <b>DO NOT RUFF</b>. Instead you discard a \C from dummy and a \D from your own hand. South has now taken his side's third trick. He plays another good \H, and you ruff in dummy and discard the last \D loser from your hand. You can now cross-ruff for the rest of the tricks.

Incredible isn't it.  

You just wonder how many bridge players would have just conceded down 2 on this hand.

Not you or me, of course.}
[Play "W"]HK

